{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/pca-explained-and-implemented-in-2-minutes-e024c832bb9c", "time": 1683005848.8851662, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/pca-explained-and-implemented-in-2-minutes-e024c832bb9c/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "PCA explained and implemented in 2 minutes | by Art Kulakov | Towards Data Science", "h1": "PCA explained and implemented in 2 minutes", "description": "PCA or Principal Component Analysis is one of the best-known dimensionality reduction algorithms. Its\u2019 main purpose is to reduce the size of the given data, keeping as much information as needed. In\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "http://artkulakov.com", "anchor_text": "website", "paragraph_index": 15}], "all_paragraphs": ["PCA or Principal Component Analysis is one of the best-known dimensionality reduction algorithms. Its\u2019 main purpose is to reduce the size of the given data, keeping as much information as needed. In this article, I will shortly explain the PCA algorithm and implement it. Let\u2019s go!", "2. Now, let\u2019s center our dataset as follows:", "In the code, it will simply look like that (I have not just subtracted the mean for each column from the corresponding column, but also divided by standard deviation to standardize the data).", "3. Now, we should find the covariance matrix for our data.", "The covariance is simply a linear dependency measure between 2 features. Thus, we are calculating a linear dependency measure between each pair of features.", "4. Knowing the covariance matrix, let\u2019s find its\u2019 eigendecomposition (i.e find its\u2019 eigenvalues and corresponding eigenvectors)", "The eigenvector is a vector, which doesn\u2019t change direction when a linear transformation is applied. You can see 2 eigenvectors colored in red on the picture below.", "Also, each eigenvector has a corresponding eigenvalue, which is equal to the magnitude of the eigenvector.", "Let\u2019s find the eigendecomposition with the help of the numpy.linalg module.", "The bigger eigenvalue we found from the covariance matrix, the more variance the corresponding eigenvector holds. Thus, to select k best components, we need to select k eigenvectors with the largest eigenvalues.", "5. I will now select top 2 eigenvalues for the covariance matrix.", "6. The last step is to project the initial dataset on the subspace spanned by these 2 vectors.", "Note, that the resulting x_reduced value is some linear combination of the initial columns of our dataset, which results in 2 components with the largest variance.", "7. Finally, let\u2019s plot our 2 components, to examine the result.", "Hope, this quick article was helpful for you. Thank you for you read!", "You may like to check other posts on my website", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fe024c832bb9c&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fpca-explained-and-implemented-in-2-minutes-e024c832bb9c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fpca-explained-and-implemented-in-2-minutes-e024c832bb9c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text":